node.text:
This week, Babe made some brownies out of a bag! Baking mixes are a great way to keep the stress levels down while still having fun in the kitchen with your little one!

This is probably my favorite recent video - she was goofy and adorable and it’s impossible me to choose a favorite part! Maybe giCantic or “my voice sounds like piglet actually.” We hadn’t been talking about Winnie the Pooh at all, but she did mention earlier that her voice “sounded weak” so I guess she finally came to the realization that she reminded herself of piglet. 😆

Anyway - hope you all enjoy this very fun and cute video! Don’t forget to tell us your favorite part!

_____________

Babe made a smoothie - our favorite smoothie that we make a lot with the new addition of kiwi! Babe loves making smoothies because she can basically do it on her own and she loves taking charge of the process!

Smoothies are a fun way to get in practical life practice (cutting, peeling, transferring etc) without a huge production. It’s straight forward, doesn’t make a huge mess, and a delicious treat!

I love doing smoothies for Tasty Tuesday every once in awhile because it’s fun to look back on older ones and see how her techniques and skills have developed over time.

Do you like making smoothies?

node.text:
This week, we conquered cut out cookies from dough to decorating! We were gifted a cookie making kit from @foodstirs (but this is not sponsored content!) and we finally got around to making them! I knew I wanted to make them for a Tasty Tuesday video, but I also knew it was going to take way longer than normal and make my editing job more complicated. I was right - the raw footage for this video was over an hour (it’s usually 20 minutes) and I had such a hard time cutting it down to a decently sized video because there were so many components to the cookies. So we hope you enjoy this almost 12 minute video!

Anyway - we had so much FUN making these and would make them again in a heartbeat, just never again for Tasty Tuesday. Haha! The cookies were delicious and everyone we shared them with agreed!

This was an extra fun project for Babe because she got to do all of her favorite baking tasks plus the ones she only gets to do on occasion, like rolling out dough, cutting the cookies, and decorating them! She also loved when we rolled up our sleeves and mixed the dough with our hands.

In case you’re new here, Yam is Babe’s imaginary dog. He and Babe do a lot together and they recently adopted a new puppy. Babe reminisced about the time the three of them made cookies like these in the video. 🤣

Hope you enjoy the video - don’t forget to let us know your favorite part!

This week, we made some muffins! I had gifted a box of @thepeachtruck peaches to my in-laws but they ended up being delivered while they were away on a last minute vacation. I was happy to inherit them and Babe suggested we make some peach ginger muffins, since we love getting them at one of our favorite bakeries.  I had other plans for Tasty Tuesday, but they could wait, especially since we had a ton of delicious ripe peaches that were begging to be used!

The recipe I found (these muffins were made from scratch - aren’t you proud, Donna?!) called for turning the peaches into compote which was a fun extra component for Babe. She has used the stovetop a handful of times and was happy to do it again. She also got to use the immersion blender which was a first!

Speaking of Donna and boxed baked good haters - I want to talk about the fact that any exposure in the kitchen is great for your kid. Boxed or not, they are still learning a ton, gaining new skills, practicing old ones, and being exposed to so much that they may not be elsewhere. I would never want to give y’all the impression that I only bake from scratch because that would be a huge lie! Most of you guys know my kitchen skills are lacking, but I don’t let that stop me from teaching Babe! Boxed mixes are great - taking a bunch of ingredients and steps off of the to-do list makes baking with a toddler or young child much more approachable. Do what you want and don’t let anyone make you feel bad about it. The fact that you are in the kitchen with your kid is what matters… not if your muffins came from a box or not! Even if your end product isn’t great, it’s the process that matters most!

Anyway, we had a great time making these. Babe didn’t get to measure much out because we were limited on time, but we made up for it with lots of scooping (her hands got a great workout!) and using the stove and immersion blender.

What was your favorite part?!

I cannot believe that this is our 81st video in this series. Phew! This week, we made scrumptious mini muffins this week using @simplemills mix. We added some extra deliciousness in the form of chocolate chips and walnuts and the end result was amazing. I inhaled about 5 while captioning this video!

Babe loved this recipe because of the THREE eggs she got to crack! She’s getting her egg crackin groove back - for awhile there she was slamming them on the counter and then crushing them between her hands. 🤣 I knew a little more practice was all she needed!

The mini cookie scooper is quickly becoming her favorite kitchen tool. I LOVED watching her scoop the muffins. It takes so much precision and concentration and she did such a fabulous job. I modeled it for her by doing the first two and then let her take over. It took awwhiiilleeee for her to do them, but she was really enjoying herself and I accepted long ago that baking with kids takes much, much longer. When she needs a break with something (like scooping or mixing) she knows that I’m standing by and ready to take a turn! It gives her a minute to regroup and then jump back in!

Babe is so funny with always making sure I use oven mitts. She has such a cautious personality - I can 100% see her as a hall monitor or crossing guard one day 🤣. I finally explained to her that I don’t need oven mitts to put a cool pan into the oven - just when I’m taking something out. We will see if she remembers that lesson next time we bake together. 🥰

I think my favorite part of this video is her new HA HAs. She said it a few times today and it made me laugh when I watched the full video. We also enjoyed bringing our treats to the beach and sharing with friends. What was your favorite part this week?

Babe and I made some really delicious almond flour chocolate chip cranberry cookies! To keep it simple, we used a boxed mix. Things are much easier for me when there are less ingredients and less steps. No shame in my not from scratch game!

I cannot even begin to choose my favorite part. Babe was on a roll this week and her fun personality really shined through. If you don’t know, Yam is her faithful imaginary dog that she acquired over a year ago. They are best pals. He’s a tiny golden retriever that fits in the palm of her hand and is always at the groomer because his hair grows over his eyes and he has a hard time seeing. I love listening to her stories about Yam and I also love how distracted she got when she saw the picture of herself in the chef hat on the fridge. (It’s a grocery list pad from @pinholepress, actually!) “I’m happy, you’re excited” made ME so happy. I love listening to her identifying her emotions like that! She’s been loving her All About Feelings book lately. 🥰

This was a great recipe for her because she loves a good egg crack (that was SO nice of that egg to crack itself, wasn’t it?!) and of course she always enjoys using the mini scoop - it is easy for her little hands to work and it makes the perfectly sized cookies!

What was your favorite part?! Hope you enjoy this weeks video!

_______________

This week, Babe & I whipped up our favorite granola recipe! It’s a little more complex than some of the things we make together. The first time we made it, I pre-measured all of the ingredients for Babe. This time, I made the activity a bit more appropriate for her skill level by letting her measure many of the ingredients out. This recipe gets very sticky, so you have been warned if you try it with your kid!

I am going to link the recipe (from @whatwolfwants) in my stories! It’s seriously so yummy that it’s almost gone and we made it only 3 days ago!

This video is much longer than anticipated - I try to cut them down to make them short but I let this one go since we skipped Tasty Tuesday last week! Expect lots of boxed mixes and simple recipes in the future! 🤪

My favorite parts are definitely Mr. Stickyhands and the grumpy parchment paper. What are yours?!

This week, we are revisiting a past Tasty Tuesday video! Babe has been feeling under the weather and decided she didn’t really feel like cooking this week. I can’t blame her - she’s been so congested this week!

I know many of you look forward to a new video each week, but it’s important to me that Babe knows that she’s in charge when it comes to her participation in these things. I’m happy she told me she “wasn’t into it” this week. Hopefully she will be feeling back to herself next week!

In the meantime, please enjoy this adorable video from last summer. It’s the oldest video I have with captions! If you want more “vintage” chef Babe, check out my IGTV tab - there are some adorable older videos from before she was even two years old!

We hope you have a lovely Tuesday 🥰

- Babe’s standing in her toddler tower from @sprout_kids. code BABE10.
- She was about 2 years and 3 months here.

node.text:
This week, Babe and I teamed up and whipped together some easy and delicious superfood breakfast bites!

The steps were pretty straight forward - just dump in and blend... but making them into balls was so much fun! There was also lots of time for fun conversation. 🥰

We tried making this with my vitamix and while it did work in the end, it definitely wasn’t ideal. The mixture was so sticky and it took lots of taking it off and stirring in between. Check out my stories for what Babe thought of the blending that took forever. 😛

Babe couldn’t get enough of the “batter” - she kept trying to get more and more. When breakfast rolled around, she initially ate about half of one before deciding that she isn’t a huge fan of them post-refrigeration. Next time, I’ll definitely give her one or two before we put them in!

What’s your favorite part?!

I always give Babe a choice of two options when deciding what to make for Tasty Tuesday, and today she was excited to make Pumpkin bread! We whipped up a delicious boxed mix and garnished it with yummy toppings.

Babes egg cracking skills have clearly regressed, but these eggs were extra fresh and pretty tough to crack! 🤣 A bit more modeling should do the trick. She also continues to enjoy “turn taking” for labor intensive takes such as mixing everything together!

My favorite parts of this video are her adorable misuse of the word genius (still don’t know where she heard it!) and how much she enjoyed the pumpkin seeds (which she has totally had before!) I also love how cooking and baking are such a sensory experience - the feels, the smells, the sounds, everything! ✋🏼 👃🏻 👂🏻 👅 👁 

We hope you enjoy this video and also hope you are having a beautiful day! We are busy outside doing yard work today.

Today’s video is a simple smoothie - our go-to smoothie that Babe can’t get enough of!

Smoothies are such a fun and simple way to let your little one get involved with helping in the kitchen. You can start small and have everything measured out and pre-sliced and slowly give them more complicated tasks as you feel fit!

Babe has made this smoothie so many times that she could probably do the entire thing alone - she loves peeling and slicing the bananas as well as chopping the tops of the strawberry. Did you notice how she picked up the knife with her left hand to cut one strawberry then realized she should use her right hand? Things went much more smoothly for her then!

I absolutely love today’s video because her goofiness is really shining through! 🤪

What’s your favorite part?

This week, I completely forgot about Tasty Tuesday! We were so busy spending time together and having fun on Mother’s Day that it completely slipped my mind. I know myself well, so I have a few boxed mixes for times like these. We had to borrow some eggs from our neighbors (who happen to be my in laws) and we were good to go!

This recipe has a little of everything: crackin eggs, mixing, measuring and pouring, and even using a mini scoop to put the batter in the pans. We’ve used spoons and scoops in the past, but Babe is finally able to use the scoop independently and boy, did she love it!

You’ll notice that she asked me to take a turn scooping - this has been a good approach to longer tasks... it provides a little break for her then she’s ready to get back into it! I loved that she was telling me how easy and fun it was while it was my turn.

We hope you love this fun little video! Don’t forget to tell me your favorite part in the comments!

THROWBACK THURSDAY

CORN KERNEL ACTIVITY

Babe loves corn - picking it out at the farm stand, shucking it, eating it, and playing with it! Last week, I put together a little sensory bin with corn kernels. It had scoops and bins and jars and funnels! She loved it. I decided to keep the corn themed fun going while the kernels were out with this easy to set up activity! I keep the same kernels stored away in a bag and reuse them all the time.

I made the ears of corn with yellow play dough and green construction paper. I modeled how to stick a few kernels in and then let Babe have a go. This activity is great fine motor work. It also is great for attention skills, coordination, and even for counting! My favorite part was that it entertained her for long enough for me to clean up from breakfast and do the dishes. When she was done filling the corn cobs, she took them all off one by one!

Does this look like something your little one would enjoy? Remember to always use supervision when using small parts.

Babe was 29 months old and is sitting at her @sprout_kids weaning table. Use code BABE10!

node.text:
COUNTING DOT PIZZA

Here’s a fun counting activity thats quick and easy to whip together. All you need to do is cut out a big circle and turn it into a pizza! Label each piece of pizza with a number and let you little one put that amount of “pepperoni” with dot markers or dot stickers!

This activity turned into a fun cutting activity for Babe, too. She cut all the pieces out and handed them out to us for a pizza party!

Have fun! 🍕

This week, Babe made some brownies out of a bag! Baking mixes are a great way to keep the stress levels down while still having fun in the kitchen with your little one!

This is probably my favorite recent video - she was goofy and adorable and it’s impossible me to choose a favorite part! Maybe giCantic or “my voice sounds like piglet actually.” We hadn’t been talking about Winnie the Pooh at all, but she did mention earlier that her voice “sounded weak” so I guess she finally came to the realization that she reminded herself of piglet. 😆

Anyway - hope you all enjoy this very fun and cute video! Don’t forget to tell us your favorite part!

Everyone knows that I’m a huge fan of setting up fun activities for Babe. I love watching her learn through play. What’s better than having fun and building valuable skills at the same time? #sponsored

Unplugged Play by Bobbi Conner is a series of books dedicated to screen-free play designed to stretch the imagination, spark creativity, build strong bodies, and forge deeper connections with family and friends.

There are three books in the series: Toddler, Preschool, and Grade School. Babe and I are currently making our way through the Preschool (ages 3-5) book and have loved the fun ideas we have found. The books are divided into sections for solo play, parent & child play, play with others, and party play. They include every kind of scenario you might need an idea for including ideas for indoors, outdoors, and even in the car! My personal favorites are the ideas labeled “busy-body play” which take no time to throw together and will buy you some time to get dinner ready or fold a load of laundry!

I love thinking up creative and new activities for Babe, but I am happy to have these books for when I’m feeling uninspired or just plain too tired to think!

THROWBACK THURSDAY

DIY PLAY DOUGH STAMPERS

This is a super easy and super fun way to make an old activity new again! Babe loves play dough and these give it a fun twist!

We recently picked up some yummy @annieshomegrown pollinator mix mac & cheese and I set a few pasta shapes aside specifically for this activity. I glued them to popsicle sticks using a hot glue gun. Easy peasy.

Babe thought it was so cool that she could make those shapes in the play dough! She used to them to create scenes, count, and to just go nuts stamping away!

The best part of this activity is how easy it is to make - you can use any pasta shape you want and they are reusable again and again!

WASH THE ANIMALS!

This is a fun DIY animal bath activity that is one of our go-tos for some fun outdoor time!

Babe loves washing and scrubbing things (like the dishes) so she loves using those skills in this activity.

All you need are a few bins with water, soapy water, and mud. Tuck the animal in the mud and let them find them and wash them! I mix actual dirt and water to make my mud but sometimes people use taste safe materials like cooked flour and cocoa powder instead.

We use our IKEA flisat table for this activity, it’s perfect!

Babe made a smoothie - our favorite smoothie that we make a lot with the new addition of kiwi! Babe loves making smoothies because she can basically do it on her own and she loves taking charge of the process!

Smoothies are a fun way to get in practical life practice (cutting, peeling, transferring etc) without a huge production. It’s straight forward, doesn’t make a huge mess, and a delicious treat!

I love doing smoothies for Tasty Tuesday every once in awhile because it’s fun to look back on older ones and see how her techniques and skills have developed over time.

Do you like making smoothies?

NUMBER TUNNELS

This is a fun DIY to practice numbers! We have done this activity with no numbers in the past - just tunnels and cars! Today, I added numbers to the tunnels so Babe could follow them in order while driving her little car.

You could also use this activity to practice letters, shapes, colors, or whatever you want! Babe has been super into her little cars lately so this activity was a big hit for her. It turned into lots of pretend play after.

All you need is paper, a marker, and some painters tape. Have fun!
